  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's a lived reality for many students and early-career researchers, particularly those from underrepresented groups. As a professor who has spent decades teaching and mentoring in academia, I've witnessed how the fear of confirming negative stereotypes about one's group can undermine performance. For instance, when a woman in my class hesitates to speak up during group discussions because she worries her ideas might be dismissed as 'not scientific enough,' or when a first-generation student avoids participating in problem-solving sessions due to anxiety about being 'less capable' than peers, these are clear manifestations of stereotype threat. It's not merely about individual confidence; it's about systemic barriers that have been embedded in educational and professional environments for generations. Given my own history of depression and the emotional toll of navigating academic pressures, I believe addressing stereotype threat requires more than just awareness—it demands structural interventions. We need to redesign curricula to be more inclusive, provide mentorship programs that explicitly counteract bias, and foster environments where failure is seen as a learning opportunity rather than a reflection of inadequacy. Additionally, as someone who values both intellectual rigor and emotional well-being, I advocate for mental health support integrated into STEM education. The goal isn't to eliminate all stereotypes but to create spaces where everyone feels safe to contribute without fear of judgment. Ultimately, this is about building a more equitable future for all who seek to engage with science and technology.",
